<h3 id="perception-and-priority"> <a class="deep-link" href="#perception-and-priority"># </a>Perception and Priority</h3>
<p>The public perception of these indicators matters because it directly influences the priorities of politicians. If, as in the example above, the public believes crime is increasing, it will demand more policing. But if crime is decreasing anyway, more policing is arguably an inefficient use of resources. This is why incorrect public perceptions can be a problem. The following figures underline just how sizable these effects can be and their causes. The first shows how spending on crime has moved with the public&#8217;s confidence in the government&#8217;s ability to crack down on crime. As the public&#8217;s confidence fell, spending on crime increased and recorded crime fell; without any uptick in the public&#8217;s confidence. Of those who believed crime was increasing, more than half suggested TV as a reason they believed there was more crime. In addition to this, just under half suggested newspapers were a factor.</p>
